{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521957"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:39:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:39:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13788"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13788"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.13,0.04,0.46,0.33]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6406"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58031"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6406"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13788"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43490"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1394"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"2896"},{"type":"tags","id":"3537"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"8189"},{"type":"tags","id":"9631"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12616"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14621"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18025"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58031"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a six-month history of right eye protrusion and eyelid swelling. She also reports 4 kg of unintentional weight loss and heat intolerance. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 105/min, blood pressure 128/74 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is right-sided proptosis with conjunctival injection and eyelid retraction. Visual acuity is 6/6 in both eyes. Extraocular movements are full, with no diplopia. There is a firm, non-tender goitre. Tremor is evident in the outstretched hands. An image of the patient\u0027s face is shown below.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient opts for medical management of this condition. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following investigations is MOST important, in monitoring for medication-related side effects in this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest x-ray","UEC","HbA1c","FBE","ECG"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of Graves\u0027 disease including thyroid eye disease (proptosis, lid retraction), goitre, and systemic symptoms of thyrotoxicosis (weight loss, heat intolerance, tachycardia). Medical management typically involves antithyroid medications such as carbimazole or propylthiouracil.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFBE\u003C/strong\u003E (Full Blood Examination) monitoring is crucial in patients on antithyroid medications due to the rare but serious side effect of agranulocytosis, which occurs in approximately 0.2-0.5% of patients. This adverse effect may occur at any time during the course of treatment, most often occurring during the first three months of therapy. Patients should be advised to report symptoms of infection promptly and have regular blood count monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest x-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely required for monitoring antithyroid medication side effects, though it may be useful in initial assessment if there is retrosternal goitre extension. \u003Cstrong\u003EUEC\u003C/strong\u003E (Urea, Electrolytes, Creatinine) monitoring is not specifically required for antithyroid medication side effects. \u003Cstrong\u003EHbA1c\u003C/strong\u003E is not specifically required for monitoring antithyroid medication side effects. While thyroid dysfunction can affect glucose metabolism, this is not a primary monitoring requirement. \u003Cstrong\u003EECG\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful in initial assessment of thyrotoxicosis to detect rhythm abnormalities, but is not specifically required for monitoring antithyroid medication side effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Graves\u0027 disease presents with typical features of thyrotoxicosis including weight loss, heat intolerance, and tachycardia.","Anti-thyroid medications such as carbimazole and propylthiouracil carry the rare, but life-threatening, risk of agranulocytosis."],"references":["Fox TJ, Anastasopoulou C. Graves Orbitopathy [Internet]. PubMed. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2020. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK549889/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43490"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13788"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20729"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20729"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xOrkMo8X9PA1mtmZgswtTk6vfmoz2e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xOrkMo8X9PA1mtmZgswtTk6vfmoz2e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43490"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-28T20:08:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T20:10:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6406"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58031